          <div type="title page">
                <l n="1">THE CONSTANT MAID</l>


                <l n="2">A Comedy.</l>


                <l n="3">Written by <name rend="italic">James Shirley.</name></l>


                <l n="4">LONDON, Printed by <name rend="italic">I. Raworth</name>, for <name
                        rend="italic">R. Whitaker.</name> 1640.</l>
          </div>
            <pb n="iii" xml:id="TCMp3.jpg" facs="data/images/single/TCMp3.jpg"/>
             <div type="characterlist">
                <head>The names of the persons.</head>
      
                <l n="1">Hornet, <hi rend="italic">a rich Usurer.</hi></l>
                <l n="2">Hartwell, <hi rend="italic">a young Gentleman, Lover of Mistresse</hi>
                    Frances.</l>
                <l n="3">Playfaire, <hi rend="italic">a Gallant.</hi></l>
                <l n="4">A Gentleman, <hi rend="italic">Cousen</hi> to Playfaire.</l>
                <l n="5">Sir Clement, a <hi rend="italic">Justice.</hi></l>
                <l n="6">Startup, a <hi rend="italic">foolish Gentleman.</hi></l>
                <l n="7">A Countrey-man.</l>
                <l n="8">Close, <hi rend="italic">Servant</hi> to Hartwell.</l>
                <l n="9">Three Servants, <hi rend="italic">disguised sometimes as Lords, one of them
                        once disguised as a Pursevant.</hi></l>
                <l n="10">A Constable.</l>
                <l n="11">Three Watchmen.</l>
                <l n="12">Masquers.</l>
                <l n="13">Officers.</l>
                <l n="14">Servants and Attendants.</l>
                <l n="15">Bellamy, <hi rend="italic">a Widdow.</hi></l>
                <l n="16">Frances, <hi rend="italic">her Daughter.</hi></l>
                <l n="17">Nurse, <hi rend="italic">their Servant.</hi></l>
                <l n="18">Neece <hi rend="italic">to</hi> Hornet.</l>
                <lb/>
                <l n="19"><hi rend="italic">The Scene,</hi> London.</l>
               
            </div>

            <pb/>
            <div type="act" n="1">
                <div type="scene" n="1">
                <pb n="1" xml:id="TCMp4.jpg" facs="data/images/single/TCMp4.jpg"/>
                <pb n="2" xml:id="TCMp5.jpg" facs="data/images/single/TCMp5.jpg"/>
                
               

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="16">I do not</l>
                    <l n="17">Stand upon wages, Sir, I will not leave you.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Hartwell.</speaker>
                    <l n="18">How woot thou live?</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="19">As other mortals do; yet I'll not play</l>
                    <l n="20">The thiefe, that is a course by which a man</l>
                    <l n="21">May soone ascend the ladder of preferment:</l>
                    <l n="22">But I ne're lov'd these climbing trees. I cannot</l>
                    <l n="23">Cheat, though I have heard there is an art,</l>
                    <l n="24">A devillish deale of knowledge in the dice;</l>
                    <l n="25">And if men wonot part with money, some</l>
                    <l n="26">Will fetch it out o'th' bones: but the best casting</l>
                    <l n="27">Is in a Taverne, when the wine and reckoning</l>
                    <l n="28">Come up together; some doe spin a living by't:</l>
                    <l n="29">And there are many secret wayes for Serving-men</l>
                    <l n="30">To live, it is not wages does maintaine</l>
                    <l n="31">All of our Tribe, Sir; and especially</l>
                    <l n="32">Those that have Mistresses.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Hartwell.</speaker>
                    <l n="33">But I am a Bachelour<note type="textual">In the 17th and 18th
                            centuries, it was common in English-language texts to capitalise the
                            first letter of common “important” nouns, probably as a result of the
                            influence of continental, particularly German, books. However, this was
                            not done systematically; one reason may be that each printer had their
                            own personal preferences. </note>.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="34">I pray let me be one of your buttons still then,</l>
                    <l n="35">I am not halfe worne out; you know what mould</l>
                    <l n="36">I'm made off, I did ever honest service;</l>
                    <l n="37">And though my fellow Vermin can forsake</l>
                    <l n="38">Your falling house, I doe not feare the rafters;</l>
                    <l n="39">By this hand, Sir, I'll wait upon you, though</l>
                    <l n="40">Like great mens servants, I do live on nothing</l>
                    <l n="41">But looks, and the aire of commendations.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Hartwell.</speaker>
                    <l n="42">Well, since you are so resolute, attend me,</l>
                    <l n="43">The rest I here discharge, there's somewhat more,</l>
                    <l n="44">Not worth the name of bountie, I wish all</l>
                    <stage type="delivery">Gives them money.</stage>
                    <l n="45">A happier entertainment.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 2.</speaker>
                    <l n="46">And there be</l>
                    <l n="47">No remedy, heaven blesse you, Sir.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="48">Pray give me leave to wet my lips with these</l>
                    <l n="49">My fellowes, sorrow has made but a dry proverb,</l>
                    <l n="50">I must toth' Taverne, and condole a quart.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Hartwell.</speaker>
                    <l n="51">Meet me at Mistresse <name rend="italic">Bellamy</name>’s then.</l>
                </sp>

                <lb/>

                <pb n="3" xml:id="TCMp6.jpg" facs="data/images/single/TCMp6.jpg"/>      <fw place="top-center" type="head">The Constant Maid, Act I Scene I</fw>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="52">I shall, Sir.</l>
                </sp>

                <lb/>

                <stage type="entrance" place="center">Enter Playfaire.</stage>

                <lb/>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Playfaire.</speaker>
                    <l n="53">How now Masters.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="54">You speake not</l>
                    <l n="55">To me, Sir, I am a servant still indeed;</l>
                    <l n="56">With them the case is alter'd, they are masters,</l>
                    <l n="57">For they want services.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 1.</speaker>
                    <l n="58">Oh, Master <name rend="italic">Playfaire</name>.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 2.</speaker>
                    <l n="59">It is not now as when <name rend="italic">Andrea</name> liv'd<note
                            type="intertextual">As the 1833 editor points out, some of the lines
                            said by the servants in this passage are taken from Hieronimo’s
                            monologue in scene V of <name rend="italic">The Spanish Tragedy,</name>
                            a very popular and influential play in the English Renaissance theatre
                            written by Thomas Kyd between 1582 and 1592. </note>,</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 3.</speaker>
                    <l n="60">This place was made for pleasure, not for death.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 1.</speaker>
                    <l n="61">There was a time when mortals whetted knives.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 2.</speaker>
                    <l n="62">In time of yore, when men kill'd brutish beasts.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 3.</speaker>
                    <l n="63">Oh cruell Butcher, whosoe're thou wert.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="64">Do not you know what all this signifies?</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Playfaire.</speaker>
                    <l n="65">Not I.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="66">My master has given over house-keeping.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 1.</speaker>
                    <l n="67">He has committed Burglarie, broke up the cellar,</l>
                    <l n="68">And throwne the kitchin out at the hall window.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="69">His house, Sir, has a superscription,</l>
                    <l n="70">And is directed to his loving friend</l>
                    <l n="71">Will pay the rent, you'l hardly know me now,</l>
                    <l n="72">I have no fellow.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Playfaire.</speaker>
                    <l n="73">You are verie merrie, Sir.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Servant 2.</speaker>
                    <l n="74">He has some cause, we are discharg'd.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="75">For certaine, my master only</l>
                    <l n="76">Belongs to me, if you would speake with him,</l>
                    <l n="77">He's gone to Mistresse <name rend="italic">Bellamy</name>’s, Sir;</l>
                    <l n="78">In the meane time, please you to understand,</l>
                    <l n="79">I Close follow my master, and shall feed still,</l>
                    <l n="80">Although my fellowes here are become blanks,</l>
                    <l n="81">And do want filling.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Playfaire.</speaker>
                    <l n="82">Lads, I have knowne you long:</l>
                    <l n="83">Although you be at losse, in confidence</l>
                    <l n="84">Of all your future honesties, I'll employ yee</l>
                    <l n="85">In a device, which if it hit, may</l>
                    <l n="86">Reward your paines.</l>
                </sp>

                <sp>
                    <speaker>Close.</speaker>
                    <l n="87">All?</l>
                </sp>

